# ArtCade — architecture authority (Qt/QML stack)

Canonical product and architecture contract. Outranks generic UI or web advice. ArtCade uses Qt/QML for authoring and C++/Raylib/Lua for runtime.

## Product shape

- Authoring engine: **Scene | Logic | Script** (not a Raylib wrapper).
- Logic Board = accessible visual gameplay; Script Editor = advanced Lua.
- Editor Play and exported game must share the **same gameplay semantics**.
- **Qt/QML editor only** (`artcade-editor-qt` + `artcade_editor_core`): QML is presentation; C++ `EditorSession` / `EditorCoordinator` own workspace + ProjectDoc. Obsolete UI stacks are legacy debt and must not be reintroduced, referenced, or adapted.

## Stack roles

| Layer | Role |
|---|---|
| Qt QML UI | Presentation only — show, input, emit Intent via `EditorSession`, ephemeral gesture UI |
| `EditorSession` (Qt bridge) | Single voice for tools, snap, selection intents, Play host, derived models |
| `artcade_editor_core` | ProjectDoc authority, commands, undo, validation |
| Runtime C++/WASM | World, sim, input, render, physics, Lua, audio — **not** editorial UI |
| Raylib | Technical backend under platform abstraction — **not** architecture core |

```
Editor / Runtime systems → Platform abstraction → Raylib
```

Domain code must not call Raylib except at dedicated boundaries.

## Three states (never mix)

| State | Persists? | Undo? | Examples |
|---|---|---|---|
| `ProjectDocument` / `ProjectDoc` | Yes | Project history | scenes, object types, instances, assets, layers, Logic Board, script attachments, settings |
| `EditorWorkspaceState` | No | No | selection, active scene, **activeTool**, **snapEnabled**, pan/zoom per scene, grid UI, open tabs |
| `EditorUiState` / layout prefs | Preferences only | No | splitters, console open, panel layout, filters |
| `PlaySession` | No (lost on Stop) | Blocked | runtime positions, velocities, Lua scopes, collision, audio queue |

**Dirty:** `revision != savedRevision` (project) and `bufferRevision != savedBufferRevision` (script). No hand-maintained dirty boolean as a second authority.

**Mutation path (only):**
```
UI → Intent/Command → store/coordinator → ProjectDocument → DomainChange → derived refresh
```

Forbidden: panels, Scene View, Logic/Script UI, asset editors, or Play mutating the document directly.

### Single voice — no dual paths / duplicates

- Every toolbar button, shortcut, and Scene View gesture for the same action must hit the **same** session/coordinator API.
- Do not keep a QML-local `activeTool` / `snapOn` that is manually copied into C++ (or the reverse). Bind both sides to one workspace property.
- Derived models (Hierarchy, Layers, Assets, Console) refresh from ProjectDoc/session — they are not a second document.
- Adapters are thin forwards — no duplicated system logic or legacy compatibility paths.

## Non-negotiable paletti

1. Stable **IDs** are identity; names are labels; paths are location — never keys.
2. Object Type owns defaults; EntityInstance owns sparse overrides; **one canonical resolver** for Inspector, Scene View, validator, Play, export.
3. Layer visual order is authoritative via `SceneDef.layers`; instances use `layerId`. No project-global layer list or parallel LayerManager as authority.
4. Scene View: **one camera** for render, pick, drag, snap, overlay, grid. During Play: no edit grid, no authoring controls, no document writes.
5. Play materializes **once** from ProjectDocument; runtime does not continuously re-read the document or use authoring assets as live authority.
6. Gameplay focus is explicit (enter Play / explicit lose) — not “mouse hovered viewport”.
7. Stop returns to origin workspace (Logic→Play→Scene→Stop→Logic) unless user changed workspace during Play.
8. Logic Board is **type-targeted** via `objectTypes[].logicBoard`. Shipping authority is **C++ `compileProjectLogic` → LogicRuntime** at Play/export load. `scripts/main.lua` is My Script / GameAPI only — generated Logic Lua never overwrites it. Do not revive a parallel TS compose-to-main path alongside LogicRuntime.
9. Behavior scripts type-owned; project scripts global ordered; Lua source on disk under project root (relative paths only). `.luac` is derived export output only. Composed main on disk is the Play/export entry; Script editor loads/extracts the MANUAL_BEGIN/END body only.
10. Logic + Script share one gameplay host API; remain separate programs. Adapters are thin forwards — no duplicated system logic.
11. Runtime destroy is **deferred**. No automatic hot reload in MVP.
12. Lua sandbox: no `io`/`os`/filesystem/network/Raylib/ProjectDocument. Controlled `require` of registered Script Assets only.
13. Audio: recipe (Generated SFX) ≠ runtime AudioAsset; Play routes via command queue, not direct Raylib from Logic.
14. Export validates Logic+scripts, materializes programs, does not depend on editor UI state or unsaved buffers.
15. Unsaved guard on New/Open/Exit/Close: Save All / Discard / Cancel; failed save aborts.
16. Feature DoD: model → Command → Undo → serializer/version bump → validation → UI → Play → export → tests. No editor-only features. Older saved formats are rejected, not converted.
17. Qt/QML remains presentation; Raylib remains backend. No parallel managers, legacy stacks, polling, or hidden bidirectional document mirrors.

## Scene surface

- One long-lived runtime/Raylib surface; Qt/QML hosts measurement and overlays only.
- Never detach or recreate the runtime surface as a UI workaround.
- QML does not own gameplay pixels.

## Script editor

- Abstract text surface (CodeMirror iframe / `ICodeEditorSurface` equivalent).
- Do not rebuild the editor DOM on every keystroke.
- Script buffer = workspace; saved file ≠ active buffer; project Undo ≠ text Undo (route by focus).

## Legacy elimination and format policy

- Legacy code, format readers, compatibility aliases, fallback adapters, and obsolete stack references are debt: remove them; do not preserve or extend them.
- Breaking saved-format changes require an explicit `formatVersion` bump plus current-format fixture/round-trip coverage. Reject older formats with a clear error; do not convert or normalize them.
- A legacy branch may exist only when the user explicitly authorizes a temporary exception with a tracked removal issue. Otherwise it is a BLOCKER.

## When implementing or reviewing

- Prefer Command + validator + ID refs + Play/export parity over UI convenience shortcuts.
- If a change violates a paletto above, it is at least SHOULD-FIX; silent Play≠export or document mutation from UI is BLOCKER.
